<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,361,386]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[281,365,361,386]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Female</emphasis>
. Paratanaidin, with 
<emphasis box="[592,640,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">eyes</emphasis>
present. 
<emphasis box="[744,863,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pereonites</emphasis>
all shorter than broad. 
<emphasis box="[1126,1280,361,386]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pleonites 1–4</emphasis>
epimera with simple seta and thick circumplumose seta. 
<emphasis box="[644,758,397,422]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Antennule</emphasis>
three-articled, article-1 composite, slightly tumid; article-3 with eccentric distal tip (apical spur). 
<emphasis box="[573,667,434,457]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Antenna</emphasis>
article-2 with ventral ridge, ventral seta mid-length. 
<emphasis box="[1256,1363,433,458]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mandible</emphasis>
molar with apical rosette of spines. 
<emphasis box="[481,589,469,494]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Maxillule</emphasis>
endite with at least eight terminal spines, at least three hooked. 
<emphasis box="[1315,1436,469,494]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Maxilliped</emphasis>
endites with incisor-shaped distal tubercles. 
<emphasis box="[649,750,505,530]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Cheliped</emphasis>
palm with slender distolateral spine adjacent to fixed finger; latter with tricuspid distal incisive margin; dactylus with one flat ventral spine. 
<emphasis box="[1031,1163,541,566]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pereopod-1</emphasis>
basis with superior seta. 
<emphasis box="[151,323,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pereopods 2–3</emphasis>
carpus inferodistal crotchets short and unequal. 
<emphasis box="[901,1074,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pereopods 4–6</emphasis>
coxa with posterior apophysis bearing two apical spines; merus with crenulate/spinulate inferior ridge; carpus with paired inferior spinulate ridges, one superodistal seta and three distal crotchets. 
<emphasis box="[802,888,649,674]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Uropod</emphasis>
peduncle shorter than endopod; endopod twosegmented; exopod one-segmented, shorter than segment-1 of endopod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" box="[199,389,721,746]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Male. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" box="[199,1350,757,782]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,757,782]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Etymology</emphasis>
. Combination of Greek prefix περι (
<emphasis box="[737,782,758,781]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">peri</emphasis>
) ‘around’, ‘near’, and the genus name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[1219,1343,758,781]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Paratanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1219,1343,758,781]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Paratanais</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" box="[199,367,793,818]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,793,818]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gender</emphasis>
. Male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,896,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" box="[199,896,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bird, 2019" authorityName="Bird" authorityYear="2019" box="[361,657,829,854]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Periparatanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mergaxilla" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[361,657,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Periparatanais mergaxilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[665,727,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[665,727,829,854]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, by monotypy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,361,1394]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,865,890]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Remarks</emphasis>
. This genus is outstanding among the known paratanaidins in having a truly three-articled antennule (
<emphasis box="[160,354,902,926]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
cf. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bamber &amp; Chatterjee" authorityYear="2010" box="[200,354,902,925]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Triparatanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Triparatanais</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
with incomplete fusion, see below) and the remarkable spinose apophysis on the coxa of pereopods 4–6. In addition, the carpal setation of pereopods 4–6 of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bird, 2019" authorityName="Bird" authorityYear="2019" box="[908,1078,938,961]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Periparatanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[908,1078,938,961]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Periparatanais</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1084,1162,937,962]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1084,1162,937,962]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
appears to diverge from many paratanaidins and 
<emphasis box="[425,551,974,997]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Metatanais</emphasis>
in having only three serrulate crotchets (spines) rather than four: although this observation is confounded by the apparent sparsity of spines for this article and others shown in the literature for some species and genera (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bamber, 2005: 719" authorityName="Bamber" authorityPageNumber="719" authorityYear="2005" box="[524,978,1045,1070]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Xeplenois" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemos">
<emphasis box="[524,733,1045,1070]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Xeplenois anemos</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bamber, R. N." box="[748,916,1045,1070]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="613 - 727" refId="ref27066" refString="Bamber, R. N. (2005) The Tanaidacea (Arthropoda: Crustacea: Peracarida: Tanaidacea) of Esperance, Western Australia, Australia. In: Wells, F. E., Walker, D. I. &amp; Kendrick, G. A. (Eds.), The Marine Flora and Fauna of Esperance, Western Australia. Western Australia Museum, Perth, pp. 613 - 727." type="book chapter" year="2005">Bamber, 2005</bibRefCitation>
: 719
</taxonomicName>
, fig. 54E–G; and 
<taxonomicName authority="Vanhoffen, 1914" authorityName="Vanhoffen" authorityYear="1914" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Paratanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oculatus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1436,1045,1070]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Paratanais oculatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Vanhoffen, E." box="[151,340,1081,1106]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="449 - 598" refId="ref31300" refString="Vanhoffen, E. (1914) Die Isopoden der Deutschen Sudpolar-Expedition 1901 - 1903. Deutschen Sudpolar-Expedition, 15, 449 - 598." type="journal article" year="1914">Vanhöffen, 1914</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Shiino, S. M." box="[390,553,1081,1106]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref30514" refString="Shiino, S. M. (1978) Tanaidacea collected by the French scientists on board the survey ship &quot; Marion Defresne &quot; in the regions around the Kerguelen Islands and other sub-Antarctic islands in 1972, ' 74, ' 75 ', ' 76. Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory, 5, 1 - 122." type="journal article" year="1978">Shiino (1978)</bibRefCitation>
: 72, fig. 40E)—it is not known whether this is real or due to artefactual or inadequate recording of these structures. Despite this, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bird, 2019" authorityName="Bird" authorityYear="2019" box="[758,928,1118,1141]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Periparatanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[758,928,1118,1141]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Periparatanais</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably has its closest phylogenetic affinity with 
<emphasis box="[211,586,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName box="[211,497,1153,1178]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Pseudobathytanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
Pseudobathytanais 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[435,497,1154,1177]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" sensu="stricto">sensu</taxonomicNameLabel>
</taxonomicName>
stricto,
</emphasis>
i.e. represented by the species 
<taxonomicName authority="Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990" authorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" authorityYear="1990" box="[957,1433,1153,1178]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Pseudobathytanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shtockmani">
<emphasis box="[957,1115,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. shtockmani</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K." box="[1126,1433,1153,1178]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="135 - 140" refId="ref29438" refString="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K. (1990) Tanaidacea (Crustacea, Malacostraca) of the underwater ridge Naska in the Pacific. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 69 (12), 135 - 140. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1990">Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. These two genera exclusively share the characters of incisor-like maxilliped endite tubercles (not semi-circular, as long as or shorter than broad in other paratanaidin genera), a ventral or ventrolateral ridge on article-2 of the antenna, and a three-spined carpus of pereopods 4–6 (assuming it is valid in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" authorityYear="1990" box="[1014,1227,1261,1286]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Pseudobathytanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1227,1261,1286]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Pseudobathytanais</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Other characters that may be shared (not exclusively) by the two genera are the short merus of pereopods 2–3 and uropod configuration. Note that the maxilliped palp of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" authorityYear="1990" box="[703,861,1333,1358]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paratanaidae" genus="Pseudobathytanais" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shtockmani">
<emphasis box="[703,861,1333,1358]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. shtockmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost certainly drawn incorrectly (Kudinova- 
<bibRefCitation author="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K." box="[151,327,1369,1394]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="135 - 140" refId="ref29438" refString="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K. (1990) Tanaidacea (Crustacea, Malacostraca) of the underwater ridge Naska in the Pacific. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 69 (12), 135 - 140. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1990">Pasternak 1990</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3)—the three proximal-most setae on article-3 belong instead to article-2.
</paragraph>
